Question: This attending clinician could improve in:

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Dr. Lishchyna rarely gives positive feedback and this can be discouraging at times. Sometimes it seems I am doing well because she hasn't said anything negative, but positive affirmation would be appreciated as she is far more likely to point out when an intern is doing something incorrectly. I think this is where a lot of the negative views come from with interns. They feel she is hard on them because she is quick to comment when a correction needs to be made and is less apt to give praise when a student has gone above and beyond. This seems to be part of her efficiency more so than anything else, but perhaps her comments would be more well received if they were balanced with a pat on the back every once in a while.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Dr. Huska could improve on her organization. She arrives for rounds 15 minutes after the time, checks her email, discusses some minute topics and we don't usually begin rounds until 1 hour in. On Tuesday, she does provide us with some clinical history, however it needs to be more structured because often times rounds is wasted. On Thursday, it is "paperwork" day so we don't discuss anything. It is nice to be able to get paperwork done, however I wish their was another avenue we could do this so we could learn during rounds. When we do have paperwork, it is disorganized. We tried to make a schedule however she doesn't like it and doesn't often follow it. On Saturday, we usually go upstairs to the Tech rooms. We don't usually begin until half way through rounds, which is unfortunate. Dr. Huska is somewhat disorganized during treating hours. When needed, she is often too busy or not around. I often have to go to Dr. Myrtos or Dr. Bonar for questions and signatures. Resource clinicians are often used to "get paperwork done", instead of acquiring more knowledge from them. When we have less interns ( due to vacation days off; 5-6 vs. 8) she is much more organized and is able to show off her knowledge. Perhaps reducing the number of interns in her pod could be beneficial. CMT: I was disappointed with CMT in May for not allowing me the opportunity to switch clinicians. I received my 25/25 choice and after a student dropped out of Dr. Bonar's pod, I approached CMT about switching. I was told that: "Dr. Bonar's pod is slower" and "Dr. Bonar is less experienced so it is better that he has less students until he gets more comfortable". Neither which are true. His interns are much busier now (albeit they are down to 6 in the pod) and he is much better at handling multiple students. When Dr. Myrtos was home mending to his daughter, Dr. Bonar was asked to step in and handled two pods seamlessly. I am paying $25,000 a year in tuition (x4 years) and it was very disappointing that CMT was not able to "make it work".

It is the responsibility of the clinician to make sure the patient numbers are fair, not the responsibility of the outgoing pod.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: - well, she once threatened to throw her coffee at an intern... I suppose there could be an improvement in dealing with situations which upset her. - Patients were not evenly distributed from the out-going interns to the incoming interns. The outgoing were allowed to choose who they wanted to transfer their patients to. For those who already had a personal relationship with the previous interns, this resulted in them starting off with 10-12 new patients while I was left with 4-5 simply because I didn't now anyone. This was an extremely unfair advantage which has left me just barely able to meet my benchmark numbers while others in the pod are greatly exceeding them. - arriving on time- We were told we have a 15 minute grace period for rounds every day. This grace period has now turned into 20 minutes, followed by 20 minutes of her checking her emails. She stated that we can go to CMT to complain if we want to but that she was told she was allowed to do this. So, at the end of the day, we have wasted 40 minutes of valuable time. - She does not routinely prepare teaching material for rounds. Some days she is prepared, other days she has nothing prepared and our 'learning rounds' gets turned into another paperwork day. - She comes into rounds consistently with a 'frazzled/high strung' attitude. Sometimes this attitude can be brought down by the interns with light-hearted jokes or conversation but sometimes it persists for the entire shift. You have to leave your baggage at the doors of CMCC and come in prepared to do your job without pushing your anxious affect on the interns. - Consistently reluctant to sign-off in paperwork. She insists that we drop our LOs and Case Reports off with the resource clinician on the way in so that they can mark them and sign-off on them. This makes me feel like she is not interested in what I am learning or in patients. She also gets upset when returning from a day off and seeing that only 1-2 competencies got completed by the resource clinician. If she could get away with it, she would have the resources do all of them. Once again, displaying her lack of interest in my learning and progress. - Refuses to give a 5/5 on any category in a competency. Not even personal hygiene. This, for example, is an area I believe every intern in my pod should be getting 5/5. There is nothing more I can do regarding my hygiene to increase my grade. My hair is neat, I am appropriately dressed, my face is washed, my teeth are brushed. Give me the 5. - She does not encourage tissue specific diagnoses. Yes, I understand that sometimes it is unclear what the pain generating structure is, but I am diagnosing 'mechanical neck/lowback pain, LLKCD etc.' way too often. Challenge me to improve my diagnosing skills! - She speaks negatively about the front desk staff and IT techs on a regular basis. Undermines them and has straight up called them 'stupid' on multiple occasions. It is not acceptable to speak of anyone in these terms let alone your co-workers. - She makes this career seem like a chore. It seems like it is an inconvenience for her to come into CMCC. If I asked her why she is doing this job and what drives her to come into work every tues/thurs/sat I honestly don't know if she would have a valid reason other than the pay check and free care.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: I understand that sometimes people can be late, but in my opinion a clinician should not be late for rounds, especially when they are expected to teach us on that day. Dr. Romanelli has great knowledge, however it seems as though he is not always interested in teaching us. Often times he would should up late and it completely changes the mood amongst the interns. As we have been very slow this summer, and most of us would only see one person a day, if that, I think we would have got more out of clinic is we felt like we were being taught something valuable and had the hands on experience. As much as learning through LO's can be helpful, I think every monday for 2 hours, and sometimes Wednesday, if it was a long weekend is too much for doing LO's. Especially when we were not getting the hands on clinical experience when we were on the floor. Dr. Romanelli also did not provide his interns with any outside patients of his own. I know this is not a requirement, but there has been no support on his end with providing numbers to the patients. Unfortunately because he is relatively new to being a clinician he does not provide this like others do. Dr. Romanelli has not taken any initiative to try and help his interns with gaining experience with patients, such as outreaches. What I found hard to understand is how him as a clinician did not know (what I thought all clinicians should know) were various procedural questions. For example, how to make long distance calls, how to bill (simple new intern questions like billing a new P during a re-evaluation), what his previous interns did for out-reaches, and the list goes on. Unfortunately the vibe he gives off is more of I'm just here for money, not for teaching the students. Getting upset on a long weekend friday that we have someone book right up until 6pm, sure doesnt show who and why hes here. I understand that everyone has their good and bad days, but like we are constantly reminded through out 3 years of classroom work and CE, that no matter what is going on at home, you must not bring the negative energy to the clinic. As interns we are still learning that, but as an experience clinician he should demonstrate that more. Its be hard to sit and watch our pod be slow and know one do anything about it. Given preference to interns that have complained is somewhat unfair and has created a hostile environment amongst the rest of the interns. Its not Dr. Romanellies fault because management is telling him what to do in that sense, but something has to change. I hope for my future colleagues, that are in the years bellow us, that management figures out how they are going to accommodate 200 students in the clinical internship. Its hard paying 26K a year and watching it go towards making the school look good and fancy and not giving the patient the best experience with Chiropractic.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Having significant autonomy is welcomed. For the first rotation it may be too much? We have gained significant ground now that the routine has been established but it took some time. More structure in rounds would be helpful. Particularly now as we aren't sure what we don't know? Could even keep in general as in TMJ, Cervical spine etc. Just a generalized idea. You have significant clinical experience and have some unique portions within your training. These are some key ideas that you can build off. Ie. Articular pumping, taping etc.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: I have no complaints on his teaching style. My only complaint is that he allowed the previous interns to split patients up amongst us new interns. Because he did not oversee this process, a few interns were given many active patients from the interns that they already knew while others received nearly none.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Most of my constructive criticism in my first few months is less about Dr. Muir and more about the process in clinic. Other than improving on letting us know our clinical requirements early on, getting competencies completed and orientation week I have little complaints (all of which are not directly Dr. Muir's fault. I did not enjoy the orientation 2 weeks coming into clinic. The interns in the pod previous were not helpful at all in entering clinic. If anything, they got in the way of any orientation we could have had. Even into our first two weeks taking over after orientation they were still coming in and impacting our time and any early/learning/teaching/orientation from Dr. Muir. I was excited when they left. My only suggestion to Dr. Muir would be to change the process of dividing up patients early on in clinic. I feel the wait in line process does not work and should be something we all sit down and discuss and divide based on different presentation and how often patients come in. I feel this really impacted my experience early on and I'm only starting to gain some momentum now. I have found it especially difficult to get competencies completed in clinic and it is frustrating to the point you don't even want to try. The clinicians are often too busy when an opportunity presents and this is very challenging when you are slow for numbers at school. This is a partial Dr. Muir/ but mostly CMT issue: 1) The pods have too many students in them. 8-9 students are too many. 9 students x 4 comps = 36 comps; x 3 sets comps = 108 comps on top of all their daily tasks with the 8-9 students and paperwork, etc. Additionally, students do not get much one on one discussion time with a clinician in this set up. It often feels like you are interrupting them because they 100 things going on. Even if pods were 6-7 it would make a huge difference for the learning experience and for the clinicians workload. 2) I think the competencies are important and it is great to get feedback on your intake, physical, ROF, and tx. I don't feel they are achieving this. I think 0% of the process should be placed on the student in organizing getting a competency completed. I think they should be scheduled throughout each time period by the clinician or the clinician pops in and out as they choose and do the competency. 3) There either needs to be a resource/resident available a certain number of times per week to do competencies and give feedback. The current set-up with competencies is a missed opportunity for CMCC and learning.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Spending more time with interns during the diagnosis process and ROF write-ups for better understanding.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Putting more emphasis in technique of orthopaedic tests or hands-on treatment.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: - rehab and exercise progression

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: - more adjusting rounds - organization of the clinic; put more care in the presentation of the clinic, ensuring ALL interns are maintaining a cleanly clinic

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: There is nothing that I feel Dr. Kissel needs to improve on. I feel very fortunate to have her as my first clinician and think it will be very difficult to find another clinician who will be able to provide the same experience that she has given me.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Taking the initiative to teach various clinical procedures that may be helpful in practice.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: More hands-on time during rounds to build our palpating and adjusting skills, informative teaching rounds but allow us to practice on eachother afterwards to make sure we understand and are able to explain to our patient, some guidance with LO's if you are aware of studies or topics that will help us

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Showing up on time for rounds. Traffic shouldn't be an excuse, we all know it's bad in Toronto. Every patient gets very similar diagnoses.during LO presentations often on phone while students are presenting. Doesn't engage with patients other than saying hi on the way in, would probably help if he stopped into the room once and a while to make sure how things were going.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Provide more detailed feedback

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Provide more detailed feedback

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Showing us practical skills and hands on stuff. We could do more adjusting round so and practice ortho tests more

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Time management. Rounds typically begin at 12:15 and the following 20 minutes are spent checking emails. We break at 1:00 and as a result, there is not much time for learning, or teaching. Technique is often skipped, or substituted for paperwork because as Dr. Huska states "technique is a privilege". We have also had multiple resource clinicians over the past 3 months in which we are instructed to give all of our paperwork to them, as well as complete any outstanding comps. Many resource clinicians have stated the amount of learning objectives given to them is ridiculous and that they feel taken advantage of. This is unavoidable as during our 15 min paperwork slots to complete sign offs with Dr. Huska, one may potentially complete 2-3 LO's, or a case report. Completing 3 LO's in a week is not effective for those who have binders full of information to present.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: I wish there was a little bit more teaching. I respect that he is giving us some freedom with treatment plans, but would sometimes love a little bit more direction. Also, our pod is one of the slowest. Therefore, there is absolutely zero reason why 9 people should have been placed in this pod. This is no detriment to Dr. Romanelli. But it should have been considered during the placement process. Almost everyone in the pod is behind on numbers because of this. It is also evident that Dr. R has less experience than a number of other clinicians. This, again is not a detriment to him. But I sometimes feel like our pod is missing some learning opportunities because he has less experience in practice.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: The first month of rounds were slightly unstructured when compared July-September rounds. I understand that we needed time to get to know each other and adjust to our new surroundings. However, I feel like we could have been more efficient with our time.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: I would like to do less administrative rounds, and learn more adjustments and rehab exercises. Although the feedback given from competencies is thorough, feedback pertaining to the way in which competencies are performed is sometimes inconsistent with what we have learned in school. It would be beneficial for the clinicians and the course instructors at CMCC to communicate more frequently about what students have and have not learned, and how they have learned it, so that they do not become penalised for the way in which they perform clinical tasks.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Adjusting his style of teaching skills and supervising to accommodate different learners.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Comps, I would have liked to have been graded on my full exam/history/rof/treatment. Unfortunately at times only one test or part of teatment was observed. I feel this doesn't give a clear picture nor does it provide the possibility for a fairgrade or appropriate feedback. I really wanted feedback and direction after my comps. I found this to be quite frustrating.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Having more rounds to have more structured learning.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Having more strict deadlines. Assigning more structured LO's

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Teaching more functional assessment during the physical as it relates to different sports or occupation.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Starting rounds on time.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Starting rounds on time. I think if we were to start rounds on time in the morning, those who begin treating early would still get to learn the lesson before 7:30, then those who don't treat until 8 would have time to practice the new skills before seeing patients.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: sharing clinical knowledge & demonstrating procedures

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Dr. Howitt is a highly respected sports chiro and has many manual skills in his toolbox. I was hoping for him to lead more hands on demo's etc. Seldom do we learn technique/practice manual skill in our rounds, and since our clinic is relatively slow in terms of patients, we could really use more manual practice and direction in our rounds.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: More structure in post clinic rounds.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Deciding who should get his time and attention and when. I strongly believe that patients take a full 2 hours for an assessment is becasue there can be a total time of 20-45 min where i am waiting to discuss my exam findings on the patient with my clinician. If i have a new patient or a reeval patient it should take priority over another student discussing a patient that is not there, or an LO or even just an inquisitive question.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: In providing us with a better learning experience in rounds.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Taking more time to go over clinical procedures/exams in rounds.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Doing paper work with Dr. Huska is very tough and she is very demanding of the resource clinicians. It would be great if we had more consistent resource clinicians. She is a good teacher, however, she seems to get overwhelmed with 8 interns, on days when there is fewer of us the days seem to go much smoother. She spends to much time on micro-managing. She also spends a lot of time fussing over having the right chair or small glitches in oscar and getting us to try to fix everything for her. She is generally good about letting us put things in to our POM's that we'd like, but, she does not often direct us to new areas of treatment. She never assigns LO's, sometimes it would be nice to know what direction to look in. She does not often talk about new research coming out, it would be inspiring to hear her talk about new research. It would also be nice to get a bit more direction for giving rehab to patients. I think it would be great if Dr. Huska would take more of a leadership role in the pod. At the beginning she let the graduating interns assign their patients however they wanted leaving some of our pod members with 13 patients and some with 2. She has since left it to us to figure out how to make things fair, obviously everyone wants as many patients as possible and has left for some animosity among some pod members which, I believe could have been made easier if she had just set up how we would devie out patients for us so we didn't have to fight about it. Finally, Dr. Huska is often late. She gets unhappy when we do not show up to rounds on time even though she consistently shows up 15-20 minutes late. She has informed us that this has been approved by CMT to check her emails but she often doesn't show up until 12:20 and then checks her emails and then by 1pm she requires a 15 minute coffee break. This can be frustrating as this is learning time that we are paying a lot of money for and our time as well.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: None

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Providing clear clinic instructions on expectations early on in the orientation period.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: She could try and be more present. The first month and a half she spent working on her political career, which put us very behind on our LO presentations, I understand she has other ambitions but I don't think I got my $25000 worth in that first period. She also took a 3 week break in August, so in the 3 and half months we have been in clinic, she has essentially been absent for over 2 of them. She does not teach enough, our rounds time are never properly utilized.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Clear and consistent communication with interns regarding certain procedures and clinical knowledge.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Occasionally pre-occupied with other aspects of his business life and difficult to find at times.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: While tough-love is effective in some aspects and some professions, I feel that there is a little too much tough and not enough love. She can be borderline (key word is borderline) chastising in her feedback at times which can be really difficult to deal with at times.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: providing constructive feedback

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Rounds, They are quite sad and difficult to maintain the motivation to get there at 7am for. Not worth the lack of sleep in the slightest. We all think this as we have all had a conversation about it when Dr. D'Arcy isn't present. She has a lot of knowledge but it feels like she doesn't want to teach it. Incredibly frustrating. I feel like I am falling behind my peers and it is depressing. I regret my decision choosing her because I feel that, yes she is easy to spend time around, but I was looking forward to learning. I learned more from a resource clinician in one day than I have from her in 2-3 months.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: A little more direction for LOs or plan of management. Sometimes I feel like I know so little about a topic that I don't know where to begin to ask for help. More direction was be helpful. Regular clinical rounds/presentations would be helpful. new adjustments, management, rehab, etc.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: I would say that there is very little to date that could be 'improved' upon. Perhaps expanding on the idea above (where we were taught that when Test X = +, it means Y) where she emphasized on what was tests elicited; further delving into what each symptom might mean would be nice but may not be realistic (and I believe this should be addressed in the courses so we know by the time we are in clinic) because of the volume of information that this would entail. I think that future interns, when they first come in, might appreciate an overview of the orthopedic tests and what their use entails (and more specifically, why a patient may get certain symptoms when they are performed). This was not really emphasized in class so I cannot say that this is something that Dr. D'Arcy needed improvement in (as it was not through a fault of her own), but it might make the transition easier in the future, especially during the physical examination of patients.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: More hands on clinical teaching during rounds.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Taking more time with individual interns to provide feedback/suggestions for personal improvement and growth.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Dr. Gringmuth could improve on his content in rounds. We did a lot of theory and case based critiquing, but I would like more hands on rounds.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Giving his interns more feedback. I feel like the amount of feedback I have received - both negative and positive - has been lacking. Especially verbally. Good feedback was given after the comps, however on a more weekly or even biweekly basis it would be nice to be given some more regular feedback so I know what I should be working on to improve my clinical skills and become a proficient practitioner. As well as more feedback on case reports and LO's

This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: following his set rounds plans, talking about business methods, providing feedback in a timely manner

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Drawing information out of us that we didn't realize we know and identify where our gaps in our knowledge are. Helping us apply everything to the function of a person and ensure that they are more than just their injury or disability. Rounds are great and I really feel like I am expanding my knowledge. I really appreciate that the majority of our rounds is active learning and not sitting around and doing paperwork.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Making us think to combine all information to come up with diagnosis, treatment plans etc. on our own. Teaching us new adjustments, as well as watching in a clinical setting on how we can improve our adjustments.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Teaching us during rounds.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: He provided opportunity for outreaches

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Encouraging a learning environment where you are not criticized or looked down upon for making mistakes. I appreciate her caring nature and the way she promotes learning and growing as a student.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: foot and ankle adjusting, going over the tissues and mechanics of joints to use better decision making

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Teaching with the use of the current literature to explain his thought process, giving appropriate feedback by use of questions, and usually being available for treatment assistance. Rounds is a particularly useful resource for learning and is well thought out and well taught by Dr. Wiltshire.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Very approachable attitude, easily available to ask questions when they come up. Very knowledgeable at patient management and rehabilitation.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Dr. Bonar was usually always present and especially good at speaking with the patients in a manner that was very direct, yet respectful. His clinical experience has been very admirable and everytime something has come up, he always takes the time to pull the pod aside to explain what is going on and how it was dealt with. He is very considerate and puts our learning experience before anything.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Teaching us how to systematically approach a diagnosis.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: She allows us to make our own clinical decisions but if I need guidance I always feel like I can ask her for help! She helps you build good habits by asking a lot of you!

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: clinical thinking.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Leading practical and informative rounds Demonstrating different ways of doing adjustments based on body type/injuries Pulling clinical diagnoses and knowledge out of interns during new patient assessments Explaining orthopaedic tests and what they actually mean Teaching everything related to nerve and to TMJ

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Allowing students to make their own clinical decisions and determine how they want to practice as a practitioner.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Dr. T is a phenomenal teacher. Her rounds are well thought out and she comes into the rooms to help us interpret clinical findings / help with adjustments (when asked). She has high expectations but is approachable, which creates a great learning environment. Never makes us feel stupid - her feedback is always constructive.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Rehabilitation oriented care and athletic injuries

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Providing constructive criticism while making you feel comfortable.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Helping me learn how to appropriately rule in/rule out any diagnoses that were non mechanical. She has also helped me learn where I need to imrpvoe in terms of my manual skills.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Asking questions that require us to justify our clinical reasoning. Ensuring that we are practicing evidence based care with our patients.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Promoting self-directed learning, giving great clinical examples, very helpful in general whenever we ask any questions

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Ensuring understanding of diagnosis, and physicals. Being able to educate on topics of interest and LO topics. Brings knowledge from practice and patient stories to educate us on unusual, or common topics that we may encounter.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: the ability of creating good atmosphere in clinic and very flexible teaching schedule

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: - having a comfortable learning environment - working through cases

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Creating a positive atmosphere within the pod. Allowing us to have fun but also learn at the same time. She is also great at working with you and directing you to a proper diagnosis.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Creating a comfortable learning environment that is very conducive for learning and discussion.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Dr. Bonar is especially good at communicating with patients. He consistently makes a good impression and leaves patients coming and going feeling looked after.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Great teaching rounds and information rounds as well. Very knowledgeable in the sports world and makes it easy to understand what is going on

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Creating a welcoming learning environment> she challenged my learning in a manner in which I felt safe and comfortable to express what I didn't know and ask for help.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Facilitating round for differential diagnosis, cases, etc.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Providing opportunity to think on our own and provide differentials before suggesting input.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: demonstrating physical exam procedures and his reasoning for using those particular tests. Also good at providing autonomy to figure out the problem, but guides your thoughts accordingly.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Being late for rounds, making it clear he has little to no interest in my learning, giving the diagnosis "myofasciopathy with associated facet restrictions" to every single patient, thinking inside the box. He is kind and means welll, but his mind isn't with us and I feel our learning is suffering for it.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:

I always feel that he allows me to reason things for myself first and then will help me refine the process afterward which allows me to make mistakes and learn from them and understand what I did well and what I did not. Also, I feel that it is a low pressure environment to make mistakes in which is an asset to the learning process.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Creating an interactive learning environment, an approachable manner. The clinician never makes anyone feel like they are inadequate, very good at communicating in a respectful way.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: -discussing case studies -facilitating a comfortable environment -demonstrating good patient interaction -following up on paperwork -helping improve palpation skills -being engaged in treatment with patients

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Being engaged and invested in our learning on both an individual and group basis. Matthew takes no days off, and he "brings it" every day with his energy, focus, and passion for teaching and the profession.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Teaching. Matthew is an incredible educator and motivator for young students.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Rounds Demos Clinical reasoning Patient interaction Creating good learning environment for all learners

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Educating

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Creating a comfortable learning environment for all interns and tailoring rounds to subjects and skills useful for interns with specific patients, and general clinical knowledge.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Challenging me but also making me feel confident

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: - Feedback - Adjustments - Business minded

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Dr. Lara DeGraauw is an approachable clinician: she will listen to what the intern has to say, and will share her thoughts in a respectful manner. She has realistic expectations for us and is good at relating things back to when we'll have our own clinic. Dr. DeGraauw is ready to help out at any point with our patient interactions and is very professional, caring and attentive with her patient interaction. Dr. DeGraauw is good at realizing when interns have slower schedules and trying to ensure that these students get their numbers (ie. distributing Rote patients towards those that are slow), all the while ensuring that the group is ok with such actions-- keeping the whole pod happy and encouraging of each other.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: - manual therapy feedback - critical thinking and making us think about why and relevance of each test we are performing - not letting us go through motions but pushing us to use our knowledge and application skills

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Creating an excellent learning environment, giving constructive feedback, and demonstrating how to communicate with patients. Everyday is fun at Bronte; it doesn't matter what my mood or emotions are for the day, the clinic environment is always easy-going, positive, and full of laughter (when appropriate). Dr. Yedon's demeanor is consistently pleasant and approachable, which has allowed me to feel as comfortable as possible in uncomfortable situations, especially when first entering clinic. I feel that my skills have developed the most with practice/repetition, but also considerably from the constructive feedback I have received from Dr. Yedon; it is always very helpful and appreciated. Dr. Yedon also has a wonderful way of communicating with patients; from her, I have been learning how to give simple explanations to help patients understand their condition, how to respectfully deal with difficult patients, how to speak up against patients' false beliefs in a non-threatening way.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Dr. Tavares is excellent at teaching good work habits. She pushes her interns to seek out the underlying cause of the patients complaint. The LO's that she assigns are excellent and thought provoking. Her expectations of us are clear and reasonable. What is especially good about Dr. Tavares is that she is extremely professional all the time. She gives constructive criticisms to her students and gives them ample amounts of time, practice and guidance to become better on any given subject or ability. Furthermore, she teaches non stop! Her lessons are well prepared in advance, relevant to conditions in the clinic and for the profession. It became clear from the start that her intentions are to make us into great chiropractors and diagnosticians despite the amount work that it might entail for her or us. She motivates us to be better diagnostically, study harder, represent better the profession, do better research and to become better people. It is my opinion that she is single handedly improving the profession one intern at a time. Her hard work is admirable and inspiring. I aspire to be as good of a chiropractor as her.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: -providing feedback -encouraging you to work things out/piece things together for yourself but knowing when to step in and help you -providing insight on complex or chronic cases -walking you through the process during an uncommon or first-time patient presentation (ex. pregnancy, acute disc herniation, etc)

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Pushing me to learn more. I'm learning far more this year then I have in the last three years, and I still don't feel like I'm keeping pace. There is constantly more to learn, more to research about things I feel I'm expected to know, but don't know well enough. She doesn't make me feel stupid for not knowing, she instead fosters an environment where I want to fill the gaps in my knowledge. I don't ever want to not know the answer to the same question twice.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Making sure our paperwork was always complete, making us stay back if needed or giving reminders, which help in the long run with time management and making sure we're prepared for practice.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: - Encouraging us to consider more than just MSK conditions when trying to determine a diagnosis. - He also places a large emphasis on understanding each patients individual situation, and how this may play into his or her plan of management. - I also really appreciated how he taught us to take research and effectively apply it in a clinical manner. - Dr. Chung has a unique ability to help us identify the essential information from very complicated cases and then guide us in utilizing this information to generate an appropriate POM for each patient. - Dr. Chung was also very responsive to our individual needs as interns, always ensuring that our education time was relevant to what we felt we needed guidance in. - I also really appreciated the independence he gave us. He trusted us to treat patients from day 1, but was more than happy to join us in the room if we approached him with an issue that we were having.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Dr. Lishchyna really makes an effort to place the patient first. She takes difficult situations with patients and handles them professionally and warmly. She is also a role model when it comes to balancing responsibilities. She is actively involved in the community, supports a family, and is a reputable clinician and highly regarded in the area. She is very open to discussing her strategies for maintaining this balance and I feel that I have learned a lot from her.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Taking the time to help us learn and making sure we know how to do something. He is also very good at challenging us in a good manner, as well, is good at being fair.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: communicating with patients and making a relationship with them and gain their trust. He also explain interesting cases in the round and ask us to talk about it and share our experience and our knowledge. He is very good in teaching time management and how to manage stress during stressful days.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Dr. Pulinec is a very approachable and knowledgeable clinician. He has a lot of wisdom to share but he does not make us feel bad the new don't know things. Dr. P ensures we have a comfortable learning environment, but at the same time he pushes outside of our comfort zone at the appropriate times to facilitate our learning.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Dr. Huska is especially good at allowing the intern flexibility and freedom during patient managment. She provides a good clinical background when discussing a case. She taught a few adjustments, sinus protocol and orthotics which were helpful. Dr. Huska takes a fair amount of days off, and it is nice to get different perspectives from resource clinicians. CMT: CMT is very approachable, they always have an open door policy. Susan was very knowledgeable when I wanted to know more about an externship and was welcoming. Dr. Decina has an open door policy, and is able to provide knowledge on a variety of topics. Dr. Jacobs also has an open door policy and listened to my concerns when I had them.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Breaking down concepts so that they could be easily learned and understood. I am not nervous at asking questions because I know that he will allow us to talk things through so that I understand what is going on. Overall, amazing clinician. Easy to learn from and extremely knowledgeable.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Making you feel included and easy to approach them.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:

Dr. Bonar's feedback after every comp often includes little tips on how to improve the items we are having trouble with and he regularly checks in to see if we have been able to improve it or solve our problem.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Dr.Chiu is very good at making students feel comfortable. He is always helpful and available to answer questions and address concerns. Over the last 3 months I have learned a lot, he is doing a great job!

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:

Her rounds are extremely organized and well planned and I feel like I have learned an incredible amount since starting my internship at Sherbourne. There has been many times when she has gone above and beyond when planning rounds, outreaches, helping with difficult cases, and supporting her interns whenever possible.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:

She is very up to date on all of the current best evidence which she continues to apply to her patients. Her rounds are always fun and educational focused on learning instead of paperwork which is something I appreciate. She goes out of her way to help us stay on top of our case reports, learning objectives as well as our outreaches. She is very observant about the attitudes of each of the interns and knows when they might need some encouragement.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:

She is also teaching us how to correctly cast orthotics which is something every useful for our future practice and not currently taught in the curriculum. She also has shown us some interesting adjustments with toggle boards, as well as her sinus protocol.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: He is very approachable. I have never been too intimidated to ask him any of my questions. He is also very open and ready to hear what all of us have to say. He supports us in our journey of "figuring it all out" and learning how to treat/ communicate with patients.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Dr. de Graauw has created a positive and effective learning environment. I have listened to other 4th year students express concerns over their experiences thus far. I consider myself fortunately to have gotten Dr. de Graauw for this rotation.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: emphasizing the importance of patient care, placing the patient first, empathizing with patients, etc.,

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Dr. Howitt runs this clinic in a way that encourages self learning. He gives the interns a lot of autonomy to diagnose and critically think about our patients. is rounds are excellent and structured in a way that ensures group participation and learning.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Dr. Chung is an excellent educator and talented clinician. The review of neurological and orthopedic tests were especially helpful. He encourages his students to seek the answers out for themselves, rather than making them dependant on his intervention. His corrections have been helpful in patient management, therapy, and interprofessional communication. Clinical pearls and patient examples from his treatment history are helpful as they demonstrate the required depth of knowledge required to be successful, and I have personally always found that descriptions of real life cases have been more helpful than theoretical cases. Education time is well utillized, and the assigned learning objectives are challenging, yet extremely relevant.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Communicating with patients. Having interns feel comfortable talking to her.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Allowing the students to struggle through a case first before providing the answer. That allowed me to think critically and was rewarding to figure out the answer, while realizing that the clinician was there if i truly needed the help.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Clinical reasoning: by questioning us on why we think a particular differential diagnosis is appropriate, it helped to cement the knowledge that we learned in class and have looked up so far. Providing a broad scope of knowledge: I have learned a great deal in terms of not only clinical competence, but also in manual skills (manipulation, palpation, orthopedic testing), as well as other areas that were weak with our education so far (i.e., real world practice/business, emphasis on rehabilitation/active care and promoting its use). In terms of patient-specific circumstances, she has given me a broadened perspective in terms of how to talk, educate, and develop rapport with patients and take into consideration their current and past circumstances (i.e., psychological issues; this was mentioned in courses like CE, but I felt it was always brushed aside via referral and a 'it's not our problem' attitude). Also - with orthopedic testing; I very much appreciated the emphasis of writing down what each test elicited (if anything) instead of promoting a test = +/- approach.
